Boil a full #kettle{}, then pour the boiled water into a #medium saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to a boil.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together. Set aside.

Meanwhile, heat a #large frying pan{} on high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g} and @sliced mushrooms{120%g}. Fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Add the pak choi to the beef pan and fry until tender, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium, then add the garlic and fry for ~{30%seconds} more.

Stir in the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @miso paste{15%g}, @ketjap manis{50%ml} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for amount). Simmer until the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the cooked noodles to the miso beef and toss until well coated in the sauce. Simmer until everything's piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share your miso beef noodles between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the @roasted white sesame seeds{5%g} to finish.

Enjoy!